@AfternoonLemon 
The above Profile file and this got my environment to stop crashing. I wanted to expand upon this answer for anyone looking for more help. 

Go to your IAM console and create a new role. You then select EC2, next on the permissions page choose AdministratorAccess-AWSElasticBeanstalk. You don't need to care about the tags page. On the final page give the role the name aws-elasticbeanstalk-ec2-role so you can easily remember in the future, and create. Then go back and eb create --single again. It should be able to launch now.

@head inthekloudz The combination of both LA + FCC videos helped me pass. Could I have passed using only LA? Yeah, most definitely. However, after I failed the first go-around I wanted new material. FCC offered a video that covered EVERYTHING I had just studied and could use as review material. It was perfect for me, in my situation. See what I'm saying? 


Actually no I didn't use the white papers. I did read a tad for the Cloud Practitioner one lol. They're boring as hell to read. Useful? Yeah of course. It's all the technical documentation lol. However I learn better by diving into the environment and getting my hands dirty so to speak. LA has all those labs you can do and tests you can take to test your knowledge. Those are gold to me. 


Hope this helped, friend.

